        s.type = 'text/javascript';
        s.src = '//' + disqus_shortname + '.disqus.com/count.js';
        (document.getElementsByTagName('HEAD')[0] || document.getElementsByTagName('BODY')[0]).appendChild(s);
    }());
</script></aside><h2><a href="lesson-75-verbs-part-4-imperatives-part-1">Lesson #75: Imperatives Part 1; आप aap</a></h2><div class="caption clearfix rte"><p>Verbs seem to be quite a recurring theme on this blog, don&rsquo;t they? Well, this is simply because verbs are the fundamental ingredient of grammar and that means you really need to know them well if you want to make your own sentences. &nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/97e7027dabb88702a17ed9eab8b5de77/tumblr_inline_mnfe3crXuL1qz4rgp.png"></p><blockquote><div><p>Today we&rsquo;ll learn how to tell people to do things, but try not get this angry!&nbsp;</p></div></blockquote><p>In today&rsquo;s lesson we&rsquo;re going to begin to learn how to use verbs in their imperative form. Before you dig through your old English school books, let me tell you that the imperative form of a verb is the verb when used as a command or request. For example it would be something like &lsquo;please come here&rsquo; or 'eat your food!&rsquo;. Can you see we&rsquo;re using the verb as a request, we&rsquo;re telling someone to do something.&nbsp;</p><p>Do you remember the three words for 'you&rsquo; in Hindi? We have <big><big>&#2310;&#2346;</big></big> <em>aap</em>, <big><big>&#2340;&#2369;&#2350;</big></big> <em>tum</em> and <big><big>&#2340;&#2370;</big></big> <em>too</em>. We saw these all the way back in <a href="http://learninghindi.tumblr.com/post/853847321/lesson-15-pronouns">Lesson #15</a>. Let&rsquo;s recap them quickly;</p><p><big><big>&#2310;&#2346; &nbsp;</big></big> <em>aap &nbsp; - &nbsp;</em>For formal situations, when talking to someone older or to so show respect.&nbsp;</p><p><big><big>&#2340;&#2369;&#2350;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<em>tum</em>&nbsp;&nbsp; - For friends or colleagues (the most common).</p><p><big><big>&#2340;&#2370;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em>too &nbsp; - &nbsp;</em>For intimate situations or talking to young children.&nbsp;</p><p>Now you might be asking 'why is he going over this now?&rsquo;. Well, that&rsquo;s because the imperative form of a verb changes depending on what version of 'you&rsquo; you would use! Sound confusing? Trust me, it&rsquo;s not. It&rsquo;s no different to how in English we&rsquo;d say 'Please eat&rsquo; in a formal situation, 'eat&rsquo; in a less formal one and 'eat now!&rsquo; when yelling at your child to eat their vegetables (not that I encourage yelling).</p><p>Are you ready to learn about Hindi Imperatives then? Today we&rsquo;ll cover <big><big>&#2310;&#2346; </big></big><em>aap</em> and the others will follow very soon!</p><p>Imperatives in Hindi work by adding something, ie some extra letters, to the verb root (which we remember is the infinitive form minus the <big><big>&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>naa </em>at the end). As mentioned above what&rsquo;s added depends on what form of 'you&rsquo; we would use.&nbsp;</p><p>For <big><big>&#2310;&#2346;</big></big> <em>aap </em>you simply add <big><big>&#2311;&#2319;</big></big> <em>ie</em>&nbsp;to the verb root. Let&rsquo;s see some examples. The verb <big><big>&#2326;&#2366;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>khaanaa -&nbsp;</em>to eat becomes <big><big>&#2326;&#2366;&#2311;&#2319;</big></big> <em>khaaie -&nbsp;</em>Please eat&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/7458bf4f067a981ed60a3044676785e6/tumblr_inline_mnfe3snUWB1qz4rgp.png"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2360;&#2375;&#2348; &#2325;&#2379; &#2326;&#2366;&#2311;&#2319;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>seb ko khaaie <br>- </em>Please eat the apple.&nbsp;</p><p>And the verb <big><big>&#2354;&#2367;&#2326;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>likhnaa - </em>to write becomes <big><big>&#2354;&#2367;&#2326;&#2367;&#2319;</big></big> <em>likhie -&nbsp;</em>Please write.&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/53ebbad2d5f2b1d2f3b82868d17536bc/tumblr_inline_mnfe41hF4i1qz4rgp.png"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2350;&#2375;&#2352;&#2366; &#2344;&#2366;&#2350; &#2354;&#2367;&#2326;&#2367;&#2319;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>meraa naam likhie <br>-&nbsp;</em>Please write my name.</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lma3uuR6IJ1qzfx8l.png"></p><p><big><big>&#2360;&#2369;&#2344;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>sunnaa -&nbsp;</em>to listen becomes <big><big>&#2360;&#2344;&#2367;&#2319;</big></big> <em>sunie -&nbsp;</em>Please listen. This is great to know because it can be used like 'excuse me&rsquo; is in English when you want to get someone&rsquo;s attention.</p><p>Note that the Hindi word for 'please'&nbsp;<big><big>&#2325;&#2371;&#2346;&#2351;&#2366;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>k&#7771;ipayaa</em>&nbsp;is not needed! Please is implied by using the <big><big>&#2310;&#2346;</big></big> <em>aap </em>form of the imperative;&nbsp;<big><big>&#2354;&#2367;&#2326;&#2367;&#2319;</big></big> <em>likhie&nbsp;</em>means 'Please write&rsquo; and you do <strong>not</strong> need to say <big><big>&#2325;&#2371;&#2346;&#2351;&#2366; &#2354;&#2367;&#2326;&#2367;&#2319;</big></big> <em>k&#7771;ipayaa likhie</em>.&nbsp;</p><p>Four common verbs are <strong>irregular</strong> in this form! They don&rsquo;t follow the usual <big><big>&#2311;&#2319;</big></big> rule. These are -&nbsp;</p><p><big><big>&#2325;&#2352;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp;<em>karnaa - </em>to do which becomes &nbsp;&nbsp;<big><big>&#2325;&#2368;&#2332;&#2367;&#2319;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em>keejie &nbsp;-</em> Please do&nbsp;</p><p><big><big>&#2354;&#2375;&#2344;&#2366; &nbsp;</big></big> <em>lenaa &nbsp; &nbsp;-&nbsp;</em>to take which becomes &nbsp;<big><big>&#2354;&#2368;&#2332;&#2367;&#2319;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em>leejie</em>&nbsp;&nbsp;- Please take</p><p><big><big>&#2342;&#2375;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<em>denaa &nbsp; - </em>to give which becomes &nbsp;&nbsp;<big><big>&#2342;&#2368;&#2332;&#2367;&#2319;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em>deejie</em>&nbsp;&nbsp;- Please give</p><p><big><big>&#2346;&#2368;&#2344;&#2366; &nbsp;</big></big><em>peenaa - </em>to drink which becomes &nbsp;<big><big>&#2346;&#2368;&#2332;&#2367;&#2319;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em>peejie</em>&nbsp;&nbsp;- Please drink</p><p>For example&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/1937af3002c95027b5ac4a97f4add57c/tumblr_inline_mnfe4sFtsa1qz4rgp.png"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2325;&#2369;&#2331; &#2346;&#2366;&#2344;&#2368; &#2346;&#2368;&#2332;&#2367;&#2319;</big></big> <em>kuch paanee peejie</em> <br>- Please drink some water</p><p>So that&rsquo;s one of three forms down! <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/2111368263/lesson-77-imperatives-part-2-tum">Next time</a> we&rsquo;ll see the imperatives for <big><big>&#2340;&#2369;&#2350;</big></big> <em>tum</em> and then <a href="../2337937750/lesson-80-imperatives-part-3-too">after that</a> we&rsquo;ll see&nbsp;<big><big>&#2340;&#2370;</big></big> <em>too</em>!&nbsp;If I covered it all at once this lesson would get way too long and boring! Practice writing your own <big><big>&#2310;&#2346;</big></big> <em>aap </em> imperative sentences, why not leave a comment with your examples. And please leave a comment if you have any question at all!</p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/1695175480/lesson-75-imperatives-part-1-aap">Imperatives Part 1</a> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/2111368263/lesson-77-imperatives-part-2-tum">Imperatives Part 2 </a></p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <a href="../2337937750/lesson-80-imperatives-part-3-too">Imperatives Part 3</a>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <a href="../5641710580/lesson-111-imperatives-part-4-negatives-dont">Imperatives Part 4</a></p><p><a href="http://learninghindi.tumblr.com/beginner">Back to Beginner&rsquo;s Grammar</a>.&nbsp;</p></div><aside class="post-footer"><div class="tags"><span>Tags:</span><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/nov2010">nov2010</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/verbs">verbs</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/grammar">grammar</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/imperatives">imperatives</a> </div><div class="bottom"><div class="like_button" data-post-id="1695175480" data-blog-name="learninghindi" id="like_button_1695175480"><iframe id="like_iframe_1695175480" src="http://assets.tumblr.com/assets/html/like_iframe.html?_v=5716f9145cbbcc5e21aa13229de5d4ed#name=learninghindi&amp;post_id=1695175480&amp;color=grey&amp;rk=EgPcCY6M" scrolling="no" width="16" height="16" frameborder="0" class="like_toggle" allowTransparency="true" name="like_iframe_1695175480"></iframe></div><a href="https://www.tumblr.com/reblog/1695175480/EgPcCY6M" class="reblog_button"style="display: block;width:16px;height:16px;"><svg width="100%" height="100%" viewBox="0 0 21 21" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" fill="#ccc"><path d="M5.01092527,5.99908429 L16.0088498,5.99908429 L16.136,9.508 L20.836,4.752 L16.136,0.083 L16.1360004,3.01110845 L2.09985349,3.01110845 C1.50585349,3.01110845 0.979248041,3.44726568 0.979248041,4.45007306 L0.979248041,10.9999998 L3.98376463,8.30993634 L3.98376463,6.89801007 C3.98376463,6.20867902 4.71892527,5.99908429 5.01092527,5.99908429 Z"></path><path d="M17.1420002,13.2800293 C17.1420002,13.5720293 17.022957,14.0490723 16.730957,14.0490723 L4.92919922,14.0490723 L4.92919922,11 L0.5,15.806 L4.92919922,20.5103758 L5.00469971,16.9990234 L18.9700928,16.9990234 C19.5640928,16.9990234 19.9453125,16.4010001 19.9453125,15.8060001 L19.9453125,9.5324707 L17.142,12.203"></path></svg></a><div class="share button">Share<div class="share-box"><div class="label">Share